The{Cherhill Roman Mosaic}was discovered in 1913 but was left underground and only occasionally uncovered. It was completely excavated by{Bryan Walters}in the summer of {1984.
It shows two thirds of a hound, or leopard, with its head missing. It is believed to be{1600 years old.}The whole of the mosaic measured 36ft by 20ft but we only have this piece left. This piece of mosaic is an important discovery because it was made by Dorset craftsmen and no other mosaics of this type have been found near this area.
There was some controversy in the village over the mosaic's future but in the end it was decided to keep it in {Devizes Museum.}
